Ertz should produce TE1 numbers again in Week 4 against an Arizona defense that has faced the seventh-fewest tight end targets but has relinquished the highest yards per reception to the position.

Over the last two games, Gesicki has been the TE6 in fantasy points per game, earning an 18.9% target share, with a 52% route share, 3.21 YPRR, and a 22.9% first-read share. Now, Gesicki did see his first-read share fall to 13% last week with Higgins back in the lineup, but he maintained a 51.2% route share with a 13.2% target share. He could see those target share numbers swing back in his direction this week against a Carolina Panthers defense that has allowed the eight-most receiving yard and the second-most fantasy points per game to tight ends.

Parkinson again finds himself in the low-end streaming area code of tight ends this week. He has been the clear full-time guy for the Rams with an 83% route share, but he hasn't drawn much volume with only an 11.8% target share, 0.86 YPRR, and a 10.8% first-read share. The Bears are a favorable matchup for tight ends. They have faced the sixth-fewest targets to the position per game, but they have allowed the 10th-most fantasy points per game and the eighth-highest yards per reception.

Last week, Conklin popped off with 93 receiving yards, a 17.1% target share, a 32.8% air-yard share, and 2.91 YPRR as the TE4 for the week. We have a long history of Conklin being a middling TE2, so you can miss me with any breakout talk. The best stat from that game that speaks to the flukey nature of that usage is his 4.8% first-read share. Conklin wasn't getting priority usage in this offense. It was Rodgers surveying the field and finding Conklin as a tertiary option in the passing attack. Don't forget Conklin had only two receptions and 16 receiving yards combined from the first two games of this season. Denver has held tight ends to the seventh-lowest yards per reception and the 14th-fewest receiving yards per game.

The Patriots continue to screw around with the personnel usage. After Henry went off in Week 2, the Patriots decided to cut his route share as he fell to 57.1% with only an 11.5% target share, 0.45 YPRR, and a 10% first-read share. Until the Patriots decide to commit to using their best players weekly, it's tough to trust Henry. The 49ers have also been tough against tight ends, so it's an easy matchup to cross Henry off your streamer board. San Francisco has allowed the third-fewest fantasy points per game and the fourth-fewest receiving yards to tight ends.
Kittle managed a limited practice on Wednesday (hamstring). Considering he sustained the injury late last week, I doubt he will play in Week 4, but I'll update his outlook on Friday.

Fant hasn't done much this season. He has a 66% route share with a 12.6% target share, 1.15 YPRR, and a 16.7% first-read share. He did finish with a season-high six grabs and 60 receiving yards last week, so there's hope he continues that this week. The Lions have defended the 11th-fewest targets per game to tight ends, but they have allowed the 12th-highest yards per reception to the position.

Kraft remains Green Bay's starting tight end. Last week, he got dinged up in the game, so his route share dropped to 40%, but he still led Luke Musgrave (36%). Overall, this season, Kraft has had a 50% route share with an 11.8% target share, 1.93 YPRR, and a 7.7% first-read share. The volume and first-read share are problems, but the matchup is pretty good for Kraft. Minnesota has allowed the 13th-highest yards per reception and the eighth-most fantasy points per game to tight ends. Kraft is a low-end matchup-based streamer this week.

Last week, with Patrick Surtain following Mike Evans on half of his routes, Otton saw a bump in work. He had a 24% target share, 1.62 YPRR, and a 29.4% first-read share. I don't think that holds into Week 4. Otton likely returns to the role he saw in the first two games of the season when he only had an 8.2% target share, 0.11 YPRR, and a 10.5% first-read share. Philly has allowed the third-fewest fantasy points per game and the fourth-fewest receiving yards to tight ends.
Last week, Smith's route share tumbled to 28%. He only drew a 9.4% target share with 1.64 YPRR. This isn't enough volume or playing time to be fantasy-relevant for Week 4.

Evan Engram looks like he'll likely miss another game, which means Strange will be the Jags starting tight end in Week 4. Over the last two games, he has been the TE11 in fantasy with a 15.8% target share, 1.43 YPRR, and a 17.6% first-read share. That type of usage is great, but this isn't a matchup to consider streaming him. Houston has allowed the fewest yards per reception and the seventh-fewest fantasy points per game to tight ends.
Okonkwo is droppable in all formats. Tennessee has been utilizing a three-way committee at tight end. Last week, Okonkwo had only a 46% route share and a 5.9% target share.

Hill is your weekly gamble at tight end. This bet doesn't feel as good as it did last year, though. He has played 32-47% of the snaps weekly, averaging only five touches and 27.5 total yards. Hill hasn't seen a red zone target or rushing attempt yet. He missed last week's game with a chest injury.
Engram didn't practice on Wednesday (hamstring). He's likely at least another week away from returning.

Aidan Hutchinson continues his DPOY march, this time tallying four solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. He leads the NFL with 6.5 sacks, which is 1.5 more than number two, and based on his schedule could easily find himself in the high teens down the stretch run. Hutchinson has forced his way into the top-five conversation and really should be a part of the top-three discussion going forward. Treat him as such for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

Montez finally showed up in Week 3, tallying two solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. It has been a slow start for Montez, but he remains a top-15 option for Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the Los Angeles Rams offensive line. Start Sweat with confidence as a DL1 option.

Burns showed up in Week 3, registering two solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and two passes defended. The sack was his first in a Giants uniform and is a welcomed sign after he failed to get to the QB despite two plus matchups to open the season. It has been a slow start for Burns, but he remains a strong DL2 option who will likely be a matchup-based DL1 during the byes. Burns should be rostered in all competitive leagues, regardless of his archaic positional designation on Yahoo (he will be DE-eligible soon). Make there wherever available.

Greenard went off in Week 3, racking up three solos, one assist, three sacks, and three tackles for loss. He is up to four sacks on the season and has helped fill the massive void left by the departure of All-Pro Danielle Hunter. He is and has been a borderline DL1, so he should be rostered in all competitive leagues and is a priority target with the byes coming. He is not always active as a run stopper, so there will be some peaks and valleys, but this is true for most edge rushers. Add and start Greenard everywhere as an elite DL2 for Week 4 and beyond.

Granderson showed up again in Week 3, tallying four solos, one assist, 1.5 sacks, two tackles for loss, and a forced fumble. He is up to two sacks on the season and is riding a two game sack streak heading to Atlanta. Tap him as a DL3 option for Week 4.

Mafe extended his sack streak to three games against the Dolphins, racing up three solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Mafe had nine sacks last season and appears to be well on his way to cracking double digits this season. If he can stay consistent, he can quickly become one of the league's premier pass rushers, something he has already shown flashes of in the past. Treat Mafe as a DL2 for Week 4 against the Detroit Lions.

Dexter showed up in Week 3, tallying two solos, one assist, two sacks, and one tackle for loss against the Cleveland Browns. The Giants' front finally seemed to start to gel in Week 3, so hopefully, this is the start of a run for what, on paper, was one of the most imposing pass rushing fronts in the NFC. Dexter is a DT1 whether he is producing ong sacks or not and can be tapped as a DL3 for Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Will McDonald continues to impress for the New York Jets, most recently racking up one solo, two assists, two sacks, and one tackle for loss. Now second in the league with five sacks, McDonald has really burst onto the scene and forced his way into the DL1 conversation. He did have two favorable matchups in a row but has another one on tap for Week 4 against the Denver Broncos. Tap McDonald as a top-15 option for Week 4.

Simmons showed up in Week 3, recording two solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Simmons has been quiet in the sack department but stays active enough in the tackle department to maintain his DT1 ranking even when he is not taking down the quarterback. Tap him as an upside DT1/DL3 for Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Young was solid in Week 3, tallying two solos, two assists, one sack, two tackles for loss, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. Young has 'just' two sacks on the season but is adjusting to being the focus of opposing offensive lines due to the retirement of Aaron Donald. Young established himself as a DL2 option last season and will continue to ascend as long as he keeps getting to the quarterback. Tap him as a top-25 option for an excellent Week 4 matchup against the Chicago Bears. Add and start him wherever possible.

Cam Heyward showed up in Week 3, notching three solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Heyward remains a DT1 option despite his slowish start but is no longer anything more than a DL3 at best. He is proven enough to occupy a bench spot as he can be an excellent bye week filler, even outside of DT leagues, but he should no longer be viewed as a top-36 option unless bye depletion pushes him up there.

Sieler showed up in Week 3, tallying two solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Sieler was a virtual non factor through the first two weeks of the season and should not be an option outside of the heavy byes unless he truly starts to heat up. Leave Sieler on waiver wires, even in DT leagues, despite the plus matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Devonte Wyatt showed up again in Week 3, this time recording three solos, one assist, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. His three sacks puts him in a tie for the league lead at the defensive tackle position, making Wyatt a no-brainer DT1 going forward who can double as a DL3/4 option for Week 4 and beyond. He will be an easier play during the byes but has some DL3 appeal for Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the Minnesota Vikings.

Hall went off in Week 3, registering four solos, one assist, two sacks, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. He is up to three sacks on the season, so he should be rostered in deeper formats. However, trusting him as a top-36 or even a top-48 option is not advisable. Keep him stashed and ready to deploy during the byes, but leave him on benches for Week 4 against the Detroit Lions.

Bryan Bresee continues to impress for the Saints, most recently racing up two solos, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. His three sacks put him in a tie for the league lead among interior defensive linemen and highlights his DT1 upside. It is time to start treating him as such for Week 4 and beyond. Start Bresee in all DT formats and consider him a DL3/4 in 11 v 11 formats.

Josh Uche showed up in Week 3, registering four solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Uche has been relatively quiet prior to getting to Aaron Rodgers, so hopefully, this is a sign of good things to come. Still, Uche should not be tapped as a top-48 option for Week 4.

Dre'Mont posted two solos, three assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble in Week 3. He had a plus matchup, so we are not going to overreact to the counting stats. Jones needs to show some consistency before he is anything more than a 20+ team league option.

Tim Settle showed up in Week 3, registering two solos, one assist, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. The sacks were his first counting stats of the season, so he is not on the IDP radar for Week 4, even in DT leagues. Look elsewhere for your Week 4 DT2.

FAU flashed in Week 3, notching two solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. He has yet to play over 23 percent of the snaps yet this season, so hopefully, his first full sack will finally help him get an expanded role on the edge. For now, he is just a dyansty league option. Redraft managers can keep him on watch lists due to his talent, but he needs a larger role to be a weekly option.

Roquan was excellent in Week 3, tallying seven solos, four assists, and one pass defended. He has been a lower end LB1 through three games of the season, but the seven solos this week suggests he may finally be getting his 'sea legs' under him. Fire him up with confidence as a top-15 option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Buffalo Bills.
Zaire did Zaire things in Week 3, racking up five solos and 10 assists. Lock him in as a top-three option for Week 4 and beyond.

Spillane continues to shine for the Raiders, most recently tallying seven solos, four assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss against the Carolina Panthers. He has at least seven solos in each of his three games this season and needs to be treated as an LB1 until he cools down. Do just that for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Zack Baun continues to shine for the Eagles, most recently recording nine solos and four assists. He has been producing at an LB1 level through three weeks of action and should be treated as a top-15 option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

E.J. Speed was excellent in Week 3, tallying six solos and six assists. This was his first contest with fewer than eight solos, so if this is his floor, we need to start readjusting our perception of Speed. Treat him as an LB1 until he cools down, especially with a plus matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers on tap for Week 4.

Ernest was excellent in Week 3, recording 10 solos and three assists. He has settled in with the Titans and is firing as an LB1. Treat him as such for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Azeez went off in Week 3, recording nine solos, one assist, and two tackles for loss. He has rallied at least six solos in each of his last two games and has solidified himself as a top-20 option going forward. Treat him as such for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Kendricks was solid in Week 3, tallying five solos and seven assists against the Baltimore Ravens. He has slowed down since his elite opener against the Cleveland Browns but has still been producing at a top-15 type level. Treat him as such for Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the New York Giants.

Dodson was solid in Week 3, registering three solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. He has been a high-end LB2 in terms of production level and should continue to be for Week 4 against Detroit and beyond.

Tremaine flashed his versatility in Week 3, recording three solos, two assists, one interception, and two passes defended. Tremaine is always a high-upside play, but his floor keeps him as an LB2 option at best during the non bye weeks. Tap him as an LB2 option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Quincy was solid in Week 3, recording five solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss against the New England Patriots. He has posted at least five solos in all of his starts this season and should continue to be treated as a high-end LB2 for Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Henley has looked better in each of his three weeks as a starter and has forced his way into the top-30 conversation. He tallied nine solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended against the Pittsburgh Steelers. He can be deployed as an LB2 based on his production thus far, but it is probably better to treat him as an LB3 for Week 4 against Kansas City before he enters the LB2 discussion once he comes off bye in Week 6. Henley needs to be rostered in all competitive leagues.

JOK racked up four solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss in Week 3. He had six solos in each of the two weeks and is displaying a higher floor than usual due to finally playing the everydown role for the Browns. Treat him as a borderline LB2 for Week 4 before treating him as an LB2 option for the byes.

Andersen played nearly every snap for the second week in a row and should be on IDP radars for as long as Nate Landman (quad/calf) remains on IR. He has recorded at least five solos in every game of the season, putting his most productive game together on Sunday night when he tallied seven solos and five assists against the Kansas City Chiefs. Andersen has proven he can produce at a consistent LB3 level given the requisite snaps, which is something he will have for at least the next two weeks. Andersen is a priority add in in deep leagues with the byes coming and is still a worthwhile target in shallower formats for those dealing with players underperforming relative to expectations.

Kenneth Murray went off against Malik Willis and the Green Bay Packers, tallying five solos, three assists, two sacks, and one tackle for loss. He has always had pass rush juice, which is part of the reason he remained on the dynasty radar even when he was toiling on the Chargers' depth chart in previous seasons. Ernest Jones is the everydown linebacker for Tennessee, but the Titans utilize two LB sets frequently enough for Murray to be considered a 90 percent snap player based on his usage thus far. Tap him as an upside LB3 option for a tasty Week 4 matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Hicks was solid in Week 4, racking up five solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. This was his first contest with more than three solos, so hopefully, this is a sign that he will be producing more in line with expectations going forward. Treat him as an LB3/4 for Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Reeder was at it again in Week 3, racking up six solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. He has had at least four solos and eight total tackles in each of his starts this season and should continue to produce with Omar Speights a non-factor. Fire him up as an LB3 for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Chicago Bears. Add and start Reeder where needed.

Barton played just 54 percent of the snaps in Week 3 and recorded zero solos and four assists. His snaps have been inconsistent with the Broncos, popping between 36 percent to 71 percent in Week 1 and 2, to the 54 this week. Avoid Barton where possible.

Denzel Perryman was strong again for the Chargers, racking up six solos, three assists, and a tackle for loss. He has recorded at least five solos in every contest so far this year, solidifying him as high floor LB3 who will double as an unquestioned LB2 during the byes. Perryman should continue to soak up snaps beside Daiyan Henley and should be rostered in all competitive leagues. Start him as a LB3 for Week 4's matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs.

Wilson played 86 percent of the snaps in Week 3, parlaying the playing time bump into three solos, five assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. There is no reason he shouldn't continue to dominate snaps over Krys Barnes, but the Cardinals are not an organization one should expend too much energy trying to figure out. Whatever the case, Wilson is going to be an LB3 option during the byes and has a plus Week 4 matchup on tap against Washington. Add and start him where needed.

Wilson played 86 percent of the snaps in Week 3, parlaying the playing time bump into three solos, five assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. There is no reason he shouldn't continue to dominate snaps over Krys Barnes, but the Cardinals are not an organization one should expend too much energy trying to figure out. Whatever the case, Wilson is going to be an LB3 option during the byes and has a plus Week 4 matchup on tap against Washington. Add and start him where needed.

Isaiah McDuffie was solid in Week 3, tallying six solos, three assists, and 0.5 sacks. McDuffie is more LB4/bye week filler than someone to start before the byes are here, but should be on radars for Week 5 and beyond.

Raekwon McMillan showed up in Week 3, racking up six solos and four assists against the New York Jets. He has ascended to a starting role with Ja'Whaun Bentley lost for the season and should, barring a trade, continue to see a healthy diet of snaps for the Patriots. Consider him an LB4/flex who can double as an LB3 during the bye week crunch.

KJ Britt played just 51 percent of the snaps in Week 3 but managed his most productive IDP outing of the season with six solos and one assist. Britt played 66 percent of the snaps in Week 1 but has been at 51 percent or less in each of the last two weeks. Britt is more LB5 than LB4 at this point due to playing time, and despite the strong outing should not be deployed before the byes roll around. Keep him benched for Week 4 despite a plus Week 4 matchup against the

AVG was at it again in Week 3, notching five solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. AVG is riding a three game sack streak and is getting extra burn with Dallas Turner injured, meaning he should be trusted as a DL3 option for Week 4, regardless of who is under center for the Green Bay Packers.

Herbig showed up in Week 3, registering three solos, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble on 41 percent of the snaps. Herbig remains well behind T.J. Watt and Alex Highsmith and is going to be hard to trust week to week, even during the byes. Look elsewhere for your Week 4 DL3/4.

Van Noy added another two sacks in Week 3, finishing the afternoon with two solos, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. He is up to four sacks with all of them coming in the past two outings. KVN would usually be viewed as a bye week/depth piece, but four sacks in two weeks makes him starter-worthy in deeper formats. Add and start him as a DL3/4 where needed for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Buffalo Bills.

Gardeck predictably was held off the sack sheet in Week 3 but still managed to post two solos, two assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Gardeck should be rostered in deeper leagues and will make for a solid bye week filler. Keep him benched for Week 4 despite the strong Week 3.

KGH was solid in Week 3, recording two solos, one assist, one interception, and two passes defended. He got extra run with Ivan Pace banged up and should continue to as long as he is sidelined. He is a priority deep league add with the byes approaching but should probably be off the LB4/flex radar for Week 4 unless you are dealing with multiple injuries.

Rashawn was excellent in Week 3, registering eight solos and two assists. Jenkins has been producing at a DB2 level through three weeks of the season and can be tapped as a top-25 option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Blackmon was solid in Week 3, registering five solos and two assists. He has been surprisingly productive in the two games he's played this season and should be viewed as a DB2 option for Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers. Start him everywhere until he cools down.

Brandon Jones was excellent in Week 3, tallying four solos, two assists, one interception, one pass defended, and one fumble recovery. He has been hovering in DB3 territory through three weeks of the season and should be treated as such for Week 4 against the New York Jets.

Pinnock continues to produce for IDP managers, tallying two solos, five assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss against the Cleveland Browns. The solo count remains inconsistent, but Pinnock is the DB7 through three weeks of action due to back-to-back splash weeks. Tap Pinnock as a borderline DB2 for Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the Dallas Cowboys. Add and start Pinnock everywhere.

Tyrann shined again for the Saints, this time racking up seven solos, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. The Honey Badger is locked in as a DB2 going forward and should be treated as such for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons. Tyrann should be rostered in all competitive leagues.

Poyer was solid in Week 3, tallying five solos and four assists. This was his first game with more than three solos, so Poyer should not be trusted as anything more than a low-end DB3 until he starts to show some consistency. Manage expectations if you plan to start him for Week 4's plus matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Harrison was solid in Week 3, recording four solos, two assists, and one pass defended. The solos have not really been there yet this season, but he is still producing at a low-end DB2 level. Tap him as a DB2 play regardless of who is under center for the Green Bay Packers in Week 4.

Amani was solid in Week 3, tallying three solos, two assists, and two tackles for loss. He deserves to be on the radar for Week 4 despite a slow start to the season, thanks to a plus matchup against the Miami Dolphins. Tap him as a DB3 option where needed.

Izien was excellent in Week 3, recording six solos and two assists. He has been impressive filling in for Antoine Winfield and should be firmly on the Week 4 radar if Winfield is ruled out again. If Winfield doesn't practice by Thursday, you can plan on starting Izien for at least one more week. Tap Izien as a DB3 option for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

CJGJ showed up in Week 3, racking up five solos, three assists, and one pass defended. He has been a disappointment in IDP land through three weeks of the season, posting three or fewer solos in each of his previous two weeks. He has proven DB1 upside and should be rostered in all competitive leagues with the byes approaching. Tap him as a low-end DB2 option until he starts to heat up. Add and start him where needed.

Hamlin was excellent in Week 3, tallying three solos, two assists, one interception, and two passes defended. The solos have been inconsistent (he had eight in Week 2), but Damar has still been producing at a low-end DB3 level and shows no signs of relinquishing the starting role to rookie Cole Bishop. Hamlin should be rostered as a DB3/bye week filler option with an eye on starting him for Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the Baltimore Ravens. Hamlin should not want for tackle opportunities against Lamar Jackson, Derrick Henry, and co.

Chuck Clark exploded in Week 3, tallying four solos, three assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, one fumble forced, and one fumble recovery. Clark will make for a strong DB3 play during the byes but should be left on benches for Week 4 despite an excellent matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Vonn was solid in Week 3, tallying four solos and five assists. He has been more DB4 than DB3 through three weeks of action, and his Week 4 matchup lost some appeal after Andy Dalton turned around the Panthers offense. Leave Vonn on benches for Week 4 where possible.

Simmons shined on Sunday night, tallying two solos, three assists, one interception, and one pass defended. He intercepted a record sixth pass off Pat Mahomes, utilizing his increased familiarity with the quarterback from his days in the AFC West to create a splash play for the Falcons. Simmons has been uneven outside of this performance, however, and cannot be trusted outside of the byes. Leave him on benches for Week 4, despite a plus matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Tre'von posted six solos in Week 3, finally showing some of the upside that had him on the DB2 radar prior to the season. He is not a top-36 option for Week 4 despite a tasty matchup against the Cleveland Browns. Keep him benched outside of the deepest of leagues or 11 v 11 formats.

Quandre showed up in Week 3, recording seven solos and one assist. The seven solos matched his season total, so Diggs is still more DB4 than DB3. With that said, he has a plus matchup on tap for Week 4 against the Miami Dolphins, giving him some flex appeal in 11 v 11 formats.

Cam Lewis was solid in Week 3 and is a borderline CB1 option for as long as Taron Johnson remains sidelined. Cam has five or more solos in two of his three games this season and doubles as a DB3/4 option for those outside of CB leagues. Start him where possible for a plus Week 4 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.

Cook has been surprisingly consistent through three weeks of action, most recently recording six solos, two assists, and one pass defended. He has posted at least four solos in each of his games thus far and has been outproducing notable names like Camryn Bynum, Kyle Hamilton, and C.J. Gardner-Johnson. Add Cook as a DB3/bye week filler who you can start in Week 4, thanks to a plus matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers. Add and start Cook where needed.

Tykee was solid in Week 3, tallying three solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. The peripherals are nice, and Tykee makes for a solid CB2 option, but he is going to be hard to trust for Week 4 due to his inconsistency in the solo department thus far. Treat him as a DB4 outside of CB leagues.
